Project 4: Melanoma Classification¶

Important Note:¶

This html file is only for whole project demonstration. The code in this html is not the full code of notebook. Please refer to individual notebook for detail coding.

Abstract¶

Purpose of research¶

  1. Analyze and classify Melanoma datasets, including metadata and image datasets), which are provided on Kaggle platform https://www.kaggle.com/c/siim-isic-melanoma-classification
  2. find the best algorithm to build module and predict the probability of condition of Melanoma (benign or malignant) based on test metadata and images.
  3. the result is evaluated on AOC (area under the ROC curve) between the predicted probability and the observed target.

Working procedure¶

  1. EDA
  2. Data Preprocessing
  3. Model build
  4. Training Tuning, and predicting

Key areas¶

  1. Extreme Label Imbalance: more than 98% training images were labeled as "Benign" and less than 2% (500) images as "Malignant". sampling technique and producing new images were used.
  2. Both metadata and images can be used for model building respectively, and also combining both datasets together to build a hybrid model.
  3. KNN, Random Forest, CNN and other shallowing and deep learning methods were used.
  4. Image processing technique were used to process the image data.

Introduction¶

This project is an response for an active competition on Kaggle platform. https://www.kaggle.com/c/siim-isic-melanoma-classification

The purpose of this competition is to identify and classify melanoma, a deadly skin cancer. The competition is launched by the Society for Imaging Informatics in Medicine (SIIM) and the International Skin Imaging Collaboration (ISIC), an international effort to improve melanoma diagnosis.

In this project, we follow the instruction on Kaggle, and build several models to predict the probability of melanoma diagnosis on given datasets. The materials provided by the organization are metadata which includes patient basic information and the result of diagnosis, and images which are high resolution pictures of melanoma.

Insight¶

  1. Missing values

Both metadata and image files show the the total number of train images is 33126. In metadata, some columns has some missing values (NaN), namely sex, age_approx and anatom_site_general_challenge. On the other hand, only "anatom_site_general_challenge" in the test data has missing values.

Handling missing values will be done before model building and training. Several choices we can choose (drop or fill values), but before we make decision, let's acquire more detail about the columns first.

  1. Unique values

    1) one patient may have multiple images in the datasets.

    2) "benign_malignant" and "target" are both binary classification, they are what we need to predict, thus, "benign_malignant" should not be included in features.

Insight¶

  • This step helps us to find out the target values (Y values) distribution.

  • the classification of this datasets is binary - it has shown by the unique function, it is worthy to note that the distribution of target values in training sample is extremely imbalance: 99% of the target value is zero.

  • This extreme imbalance of Y values may cause a dilemma:

    • you will get a good validating accuracy, (validation dataset is a randomly selected subset of training dataset, it is reasonable to assume that randomly guess may get >90% accuracy), but the test datasets may differ from the training dataset and the test accuracy is low;
    • or you will get both high validating accuracy and test accuracy - the problem is any algorithm will do the same thing.
    • the real problem is that it makes more hard to identify malignant melanoma, because the corresponding samples are too few to identify features.
  • Therefore, having too many benign samples does not help us to identify malignant melanoma. This may imply that we could reduce benign samples to reduce over-fitting issue. And we will reduce benign samples in training sections.

Meta Data Preprocessing¶

In this section, we will begin with handling missing values and encoding the category columns:

  • first step is handling missing values. Since test data also has missing value, we cannot simply drop all the NaN rows. In this case, we can fill with the most common one;
  • "age_approx" is a numerical column, what we need to do is normalization, we will use MinMaxScaler to normalize the column

  • regarding category columns: "sex", "anatom_site_general_challenge", we have explore that those two columns have correlation with the target diagnose result. we will use different encoding for the two columns:

    • "sex", is a binary classification, we will use conditional expression to convert boolean results to numerical results;
    • "anatom_site_general_challenge", only have 6 unique values and those values we think are equally important, so we will try "OneHotEncoder".

# randomly select a certain number of samples labelled as "benign"
def random_selection(df1, df2, k_samples=10000):
    random_index = random.sample(df1.index.to_list(), k_samples)
    random_df = df1.loc[random_index]
    select_df = pd.concat([random_df, df2])
    select_df.sort_index(inplace=True)
    return select_df

malignant_train_df = train_df[cond2]
benign_train_df = train_df[cond1]

In [118]:
def plotImages(images_arr, labels=None, number=10):
    fig, axes = plt.subplots(1, number, figsize=(20,20))
    axes = axes.flatten()
    if labels is None:
        labels = ['Unknown'] * number
    
    for img, label, ax in zip(images_arr,labels, axes):
        ax.imshow(img)
        ax.axis('off')
        ax.set_title(label)
    plt.tight_layout()
    plt.show()

Picture discovery¶

We found that the pictures of malignant melanin in the picture collection are much less than benign melanin, so we made an averaging, reduced a large number of benign melanin pictures, and then merged less melanin pictures with all the malignant melanin into a new averaged Photo dataset. Another reason ,we discover that Compared with a large number of benign melanin pictures, a small number of benign melanin pictures can get a better model

Function for eda explanation

When I was processing these photos, I found that some of the melanin will be covered by the hair, then if we extract the RGB of the melanin, we will definitely extract the hair color, which will confuse the model. So I removed the hair through the HSV color pipeline. It will judge according to the body part whether it may appear in the place with hair, and use the hsv method

feature extraction¶

As we knew KNN is machine learning , it's different to the deep learning. Such as CNN deep learning can get the feature by itself.
KNN have to fetch the feature by human.I extracted the RGB of the picture as the feature of the picture
Extraction steps:

1. Part of the picture is cropped because we found that the location of melanin is basically in the middle of the picture.
2.0 Remove the noise of the picture through several filters, so that I can get the contour of the melanin.
2.1 Hair appears in some pictures, I used a filter to filter out the hair outside the melanin contour.
3. Get the contour, then get the RGB in the contour
4. I found that by using HSV channel, you can remove most of the hair in the melanin contour.
5. Get the mean and Standard Deviation of RGB.
6. Through addition and subtraction, get the highest , lowest and mean value of RGB. It will represent in this RGB range, it belongs to melanin
In [126]:
def load_img(path,body,tr_B_lower,tr_B_m,tr_B_upper,tr_G_lower,tr_G_m,tr_G_upper,tr_R_lower,tr_R_m,tr_R_upper):  
    # Read the image and perfrom an OTSU threshold
    img = cv2.imread(path)
    h, w = img.shape[:2]
    center_h = int(h/2)
    center_w = int(w/2)
    half_center_h = int(center_h/2)
    half_center_w = int(center_w/2)
    img = img[center_h-half_center_h-10:center_h+half_center_h+10,center_w-half_center_w-10:center_w+half_center_w+10]

    kernel = np.ones((15,15),np.uint8)

    # Perform closing to remove hair and blur the image
    closing = cv2.morphologyEx(img,cv2.MORPH_CLOSE,kernel, iterations = 2)
    blur = cv2.blur(closing,(15,15))

    # Binarize the image
    gray = cv2.cvtColor(blur,cv2.COLOR_BGR2GRAY)
    _,thresh = cv2.threshold(gray,0,255,cv2.THRESH_BINARY_INV+cv2.THRESH_OTSU)


    # Search for contours and select the biggest one
    contours, hierarchy =     cv2.findContours(thresh,cv2.RETR_TREE,cv2.CHAIN_APPROX_NONE)
    cnt = max(contours, key=cv2.contourArea)

    # Create a new mask for the result image
    h, w = img.shape[:2]
    mask = np.zeros((h, w), np.uint8)

    # Draw the contour on the new mask and perform the bitwise operation
    cv2.drawContours(mask, [cnt],-1, 255, -1)
    res = cv2.bitwise_and(img, img, mask=mask)
    if body==1:
        hsv = cv2.cvtColor(res,cv2.COLOR_BGR2HSV)
        lower_red=np.array([0,80,80])#red
        upper_red=np.array([255,255,255])
        mask=cv2.inRange(hsv,lower_red,upper_red)
        res=cv2.bitwise_and(res,res,mask=mask)
        res = cv2.cvtColor(res,cv2.COLOR_BGR2RGB)
    else:
        res = cv2.cvtColor(res,cv2.COLOR_BGR2RGB)

    (mean,std)=cv2.meanStdDev(res,mask=mask)

    tr_B_lower.append((mean[0]-std[0])[0])
    tr_B_upper.append((mean[0]+std[0])[0])
    tr_B_m.append((mean[0])[0])
    

    tr_G_lower.append((mean[1]-std[1])[0])
    tr_G_upper.append((mean[1]+std[1])[0])
    tr_G_m.append((mean[1])[0])
    
    
    tr_R_lower.append((mean[2]-std[2])[0])
    tr_R_upper.append((mean[2]+std[2])[0])
    tr_R_m.append((mean[2])[0])

In [144]:



    


def calculate_regression_goodness_of_fit(ys, y_hat):
    ss_total = 0
    ss_residual = 0
    ss_regression = 0
    y_mean = ys.mean()
    
    for i in range(len(ys)):
        ss_total += np.square(ys[i] - y_mean)
        ss_residual += np.square(ys[i] - y_hat[i])
        ss_regression += np.square(y_hat[i] - y_mean)
    
    r_square = ss_regression / ss_total
    rmse = np.sqrt( ss_residual / float(len(ys)) )
    return r_square, rmse

Multi-task Learning Model¶
Below we would use the Multi-task Learning concept to setup the model for training and prediction. Multi-task Learning is a subfield of machine learning in which multiple learning tasks are solved at the same time. It can accept different input data with same target or different input data and different target. Here we have 2 different input data, image data and meta data, and same training target. Since the CNN deep learning model are very good at image data training, we can setup a Multi-task Learning model combining a CNN model for image data input and a simple MLP model for meta data input.


CNN: Convolutional neural network, CNN is a class of deep neural networks, most commonly applied to analyzing visual imagery.
MLP: Multilayer perceptron, MLP is a class of feedforward artificial neural network that composed of multiple layers of perceptrons (with threshold activation).


And to improve the model accuracy, we'd like to take some more ways to process the input data before feed into the model.















Sampling would be required¶
We can see there is huge gap between number of the normal samples and the Melanoma samples. If we put both samples directly into model training, it may show good training accuracy but actually it may not correctly identify the Melanoma cases due to small provided samples. Therefore, we actually don't need to load all the normal samples but it would be better to make sure all the Melanoma samples are used for model training. Furthermore, it would be better to find ways to produce more Melanoma samples for training, like rotate the image for 90 degree as a new sample.

Crop center of image¶
Checking the provided images of patient skin, we noticed that the lesion are mainly in the center of the image, the surrounding part of the lesion are mainly skin and hairs. To reduce the noice of the data, to crop the center part of the image would be a good way to improve the accuracy.


So below we define a function to crop the center part by providing the new width and height value and an example to show the difference between orignal image and cropped image.













In [9]:



    


# define the function to crop the center part of the image
def crop_center(img, cropx, cropy):
    y,x = img.shape[1:3]
    startx = x//2-(cropx//2)
    starty = y//2-(cropy//2)    
    return img[:,starty:starty+cropy,startx:startx+cropx:,]

Customized Image Generator¶
There are total more than 30k images, it will cost huge memory to load all the images at once, especially with higher resolution loading parameter. At the same time, it has to keep reasonable resolution for the images to make sure the model training can locate the difference of different images. Therefore, using an image generator to provide the training and validation data would be a good solution.


Keras provided build-in ImageDataGenerator to generate the images data by defined batch size. But it also had some limitation if the provided API don't fulfill your model requirement. You can write your own image generator but it cannot support the multi-threading. Keras provided a solution that you can write your own image generator inherited from the tf.keras.utils.Sequence() class which enable multi-threading support.


Below we have written our own image generator inherited from Sequence() class providing following functions:


    

  • Sampling a given size of normal images and all the Melanoma images for training, it will highly improve the image loading time. It also helped to balance the data volume size of normal and Melanoma images. 
    • 

  • Randomly select the normal image samples during the start of each epoch. 
    • 

  • Crop the center part of the selected images as the output for model training. 
    • 

  • Produce more training samples of Melanoma images by rotating the original images by 90 degrees and use the same metadata of original images. 
    • 

  • Output both image data and metadata for Multi-task model training
    • 














In [14]:



    


class Train_Generator(Sequence):

    def __init__(self, train_df, num_samples=5000, batch_size=50, target_dim=(400, 400)):
        
        # separate the data in normal and cancer status
        normal_data = train_df[train_df['target'] == 0]
        cancer_data = train_df[train_df['target'] == 1]

        # shuffle the normal data and take num_samples records only to save training time
        normal_data = normal_data.sample(frac=1).reset_index(drop=True)
        normal_data = normal_data[:num_samples] 
        
        # append the cancer data and product X and y for model training data and shuffle the sequence
        normal_data = normal_data.append(cancer_data, ignore_index=True)
        normal_data = normal_data.sample(frac=1).reset_index(drop=True)
        x_image_set = normal_data['file_path']
        y_set = normal_data['target']
        cols = [i for i in range(10)]
        cols.append('age_approx')
        x_meta_set = normal_data[cols]
            
        self.df = train_df
        self.x_image, self.x_meta, self.y = x_image_set, x_meta_set, y_set
        self.samples = num_samples
        self.batch_size = batch_size
        self.target_size = target_dim
        

    def __len__(self):
        return math.ceil(len(self.x_image) / self.batch_size)

    def __getitem__(self, idx):
        
        # Load the images by batch size
        batch_x = self.x_image[idx * self.batch_size:(idx + 1) * self.batch_size]
        batch_y = np.array(self.y[idx * self.batch_size:(idx + 1) * self.batch_size])
        image_x = np.array([img_to_array(load_img(img, target_size=self.target_size)) for img in batch_x])
        image_x /= 255.0
        
        crop_image_x = crop_center(image_x, self.target_size[0]-100, self.target_size[1]-100) # crop center of image
        meta_x = self.x_meta[idx * self.batch_size:(idx + 1) * self.batch_size] # output meta data
        
        # Create new data with ratating image for 90 degree for Melanoma images
        for i in range(len(batch_y)):
            if batch_y[i] == 1:
                new_img = np.rot90(crop_image_x[i])
                crop_image_x = np.concatenate((crop_image_x, [new_img]))
                batch_y = np.concatenate((batch_y, [1]))
                new_meta = meta_x.iloc[i]
                meta_x = meta_x.append(new_meta)      

        return [crop_image_x, meta_x], batch_y
    
    def on_epoch_end(self):
        normal_data = self.df[self.df['target'] == 0]
        cancer_data = self.df[self.df['target'] == 1]
        
        # shuffle the normal images in each epoch ends
        normal_data = normal_data.sample(frac=1).reset_index(drop=True)
        normal_data = normal_data[:self.samples] 
        
        normal_data = normal_data.append(cancer_data, ignore_index=True)
        normal_data = normal_data.sample(frac=1).reset_index(drop=True)
        x_image_set = normal_data['file_path']
        y_set = normal_data['target']
        cols = [i for i in range(10)]
        cols.append('age_approx')
        x_meta_set = normal_data[cols]
        
        self.x_image, self.x_meta, self.y = x_image_set, x_meta_set, y_set



    















Multi-task Learning¶
To implement the Multi-task learning model, create 2 functions which one is for CNN and another for MLP.


For CNN model, it would go to setup 3 types of layers, the convolutional layer, pooling layer and fully connected layer.


    

  • Convolutional layer: Apply filters to extract the images features. It consider the influence of nearby pixels
    • 

  • Pooling layer：Reduce dimensionality and extract maximum of average of a region
    • 

  • Fully connected layer: Aggregate information from final feature maps
    • 



For MLP model, it's more simple as a feed-forward neural network. It just have the fully connected layer which is enough for the simple data format of metadata.













In [15]:



    


# create the CNN model
def create_cnn(input_dim):

    model = Sequential()

    # Convolutional layer and max pooling layer
    model.add(Conv2D(32, (3, 3), activation='relu', input_shape=input_dim))
    model.add(MaxPooling2D(pool_size=(2, 2)))

    model.add(Conv2D(64, (3, 3), activation='relu'))
    model.add(MaxPooling2D(pool_size=(2, 2)))
    #model.add(Dropout(0.25)) # we don't need dropout layer here as the optimizer would do the job

    model.add(Conv2D(128, (3, 3), activation='relu'))
    model.add(MaxPooling2D(pool_size=(2, 2)))

    model.add(Conv2D(128, (3, 3), activation='relu'))
    model.add(MaxPooling2D(pool_size=(2, 2)))
    #model.add(Dropout(0.25))

    model.add(Flatten())
    model.add(Dense(2048, activation='relu', name='deep_1'))
    model.add(Dense(1024, activation='relu', name='deep_2'))
    model.add(Dense(256, activation='relu'))
    #model.add(Dropout(0.5))
   
    return model



    













In [16]:



    


# create the MLP model
def create_mlp(input_dim):
    
    model = Sequential()
    model.add(Dense(16, input_dim=input_dim, activation="relu"))
    model.add(Dense(8, activation="relu"))
   
    return model



    













In [17]:



    


# Combine the CNN and MLP model
mlp = create_mlp(11)
cnn = create_cnn((300, 300, 3))

combinedInput = concatenate([mlp.output, cnn.output])

# Adding the classification layer
x = Dense(64, activation="relu")(combinedInput)
x = Dense(1, activation="sigmoid")(x)

model = Model(inputs=[cnn.input, mlp.input], outputs=x)

model.compile(loss='binary_crossentropy',
                  optimizer=optimizers.RMSprop(lr=1e-4),
                  metrics=['accuracy'])
model.summary()

Test Image Generator and Prediction¶
After the model is trained, a test data image generator is required to prepare the data for prediction. It's more simple compare to the training image generator. It would only require to load the test images as array format by batch size. And then output the data including metadata prepared for model prediction.


And this generator also support multi-thread so that the prediction can save processing time with worker thread as 6.













In [19]:



    


# The image generator for the test dataset
class Test_Generator(Sequence):

    def __init__(self, x_image, x_meta, batch_size=50, target_dim=(200, 200)):
        self.x_files = x_image
        self.x_meta = x_meta
        self.batch_size = batch_size
        self.target_size = target_dim

    def __len__(self):
        return math.ceil(len(self.x_files) / self.batch_size)

    def __getitem__(self, idx):

        batch_x = self.x_files[idx * self.batch_size:(idx + 1) * self.batch_size]
        image_x = np.array([img_to_array(load_img(img, target_size=self.target_size)) for img in batch_x])
        image_x /= 255.0
        
        crop_image_x = crop_center(image_x, self.target_size[0]-100, self.target_size[1]-100)     
        meta_x = self.x_meta[idx * self.batch_size:(idx + 1) * self.batch_size]

        return [crop_image_x, meta_x]

Summary¶
We have used different model to train the data and come out the prediction result. Among all our models, the Mutli-task Learning model achieve the best score of 0.793. And we have some good findings to process an image dataset.


Long time consuming and large memory usage on image dataset¶
The main bottle neck are spending most of the time in loading the images into dataset. The higher resolution you set for loading the image, the longer time consuming and higher memory usage is required. Therefore, we take different ways to solve the problem. Using image generator to load them by batch, enable multi-thread to reduce loading time, directly calculate RGB data and store average() etc to reduce memory usage.


Identify image pattern is important¶
To solve an image classification problem, identify the image pattern(features) is important. We mainly took 2 ways. One is to extract the RGB information of the image and perform some of the image processing technique to come out the key image pattern. Another one is to use CNN model and make use of convolutional layer/pooling layer to extract image features.


sampling is required to balance samples in different target¶
There is huge gap between the normal samples and the Melanoma samples. It need to find ways to balance a bit the training samples of the 2 different targets. Otherwise the model may have very good training accuracy but actually it cannot identify the Melanoma cases. We have tried some ways to solve this problem through sampling method and producing more new samples.


Further improvement¶
We thought the model we have built can be used to detect the Melanoma cases. When the patient upload a picture of the skin image, the model can come out a probability value to indicate how close it's Melanoma. But still, there are lots of improvement areas to be investigate to improve the model accuracy. For example, we haven't finished the modeling for the case that one patient have several images, considering this situation to improve accuracy.
